<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>
<chapter subject="Biology" id="302" name="Biological Classification">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Who is the father of biological classification?</text>
            <option id="A">Aristotle</option><option id="B">Linnaeus</option><option id="C">Whittaker</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>He classified plants into herbs, shrubs, trees and animals based on red blood.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Who gave the Two Kingdom classification (Plantae and Animalia)?</text>
            <option id="A">Carolus Linnaeus</option><option id="B">Aristotle</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Based on presence/absence of cell wall and locomotion.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Who proposed the Five Kingdom system of classification?</text>
            <option id="A">R.H. Whittaker (1969)</option><option id="B">Bentham</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Criteria: Cell structure, thallus, nutrition, reproduction, phylogeny.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Organisms belonging to Kingdom Monera are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Prokaryotic</option><option id="B">Eukaryotic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lack a well-defined nucleus and membrane-bound organelles.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sole members of Kingdom Monera are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Bacteria</option><option id="B">Amoeba</option><option id="C">Fungi</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Most abundant and diverse prokaryotes.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Spherical bacteria are called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Coccus</option><option id="B">Bacillus</option><option id="C">Spirillum</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Singular: Coccus, Plural: Cocci.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Rod-shaped bacteria are called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Bacillus</option><option id="B">Coccus</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: E. coli.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Comma-shaped bacteria are called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Vibrio</option><option id="B">Spirillum</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Vibrio cholerae.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Bacteria found in extreme salty areas are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Halophiles</option><option id="B">Methanogens</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Part of Archaebacteria.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Bacteria found in hot springs are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Thermoacidophiles</option><option id="B">Halophiles</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Survival due to different cell wall structure.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Bacteria found in marshy areas and gut of ruminants? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Methanogens</option><option id="B">Cyanobacteria</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Produce methane (biogas) from dung.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cyanobacteria are also known as ____ algae.</text>
            <option id="A">Blue-Green</option><option id="B">Red</option><option id="C">Green</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Have chlorophyll 'a' similar to green plants.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Specialized cells used for Nitrogen fixation in Nostoc and Anabaena are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Heterocysts</option><option id="B">Spores</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Thick-walled anaerobic cells.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Smallest living cells known that lack a cell wall are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Mycoplasma</option><option id="B">Bacteria</option><option id="C">Yeast</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>PPLO (Pleuro Pneumonia Like Organisms).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Kingdom Protista includes all single-celled ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Eukaryotes</option><option id="B">Prokaryotes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Form a link with fungi, plants and animals.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Golden algae and Diatoms are included in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Chrysophytes</option><option id="B">Dinoflagellates</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Found in freshwater and marine environments.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Accumulation of diatom cell walls forms ____ earth.</text>
            <option id="A">Diatomaceous</option><option id="B">Plastic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used in polishing and filtration.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Example of Euglenoids is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Euglena</option><option id="B">Paramoecium</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Shows both autotrophic and heterotrophic nutrition.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Euglena has a protein-rich layer called ____ instead of cell wall.</text>
            <option id="A">Pellicle</option><option id="B">Capsule</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Makes their body flexible.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Saprophytic protists that aggregate to form Plasmodium are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Slime Moulds</option><option id="B">Protozoans</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Move along decaying twigs engulfing organic material.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Amoeba uses ____ for capturing prey.</text>
            <option id="A">Pseudopodia</option><option id="B">Flagella</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>False feet.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sleeping sickness is caused by ____ protozoan.</text>
            <option id="A">Trypanosoma</option><option id="B">Plasmodium</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Flagellated parasite.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Malaria is caused by ____ protozoan.</text>
            <option id="A">Plasmodium</option><option id="B">Amoeba</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sporozoan with infectious spore stage.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Kingdom Fungi consists of ____ organisms.</text>
            <option id="A">Heterotrophic</option><option id="B">Autotrophic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Absorptive nutrition.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cell walls of Fungi are composed of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Chitin and Polysaccharides</option><option id="B">Cellulose</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Chitin is a nitrogen-containing glucose polymer.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Network of hyphae in fungi is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Mycelium</option><option id="B">Thallus</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Can be septate or coenocytic.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Symbiotic association of fungi with algae is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Lichen</option><option id="B">Mycorrhiza</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Phycobiont + Mycobiont.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Symbiotic association of fungi with roots of higher plants is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Mycorrhiza</option><option id="B">Lichen</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Helps in phosphorus absorption.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Bread mould is scientificly known as ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Rhizopus</option><option id="B">Mucor</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Phycomycete fungus.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Penicillium belongs to ____ group of fungi.</text>
            <option id="A">Ascomycetes (Sac fungi)</option><option id="B">Basidiomycetes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Source of first antibiotic.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Agaricus (Mushroom) belongs to ____ group.</text>
            <option id="A">Basidiomycetes (Club fungi)</option><option id="B">Ascomycetes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Produce basidiospores exogenously.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Fungi Imperfecti refers to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Deuteromycetes</option><option id="B">Phycomycetes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sexual stage is not yet known.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Virus means ____ in Latin.</text>
            <option id="A">Venom / Poisonous fluid</option><option id="B">Cell</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Name given by Pasteur / Ivanowsky.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Viruses consist of genetic material (DNA or RNA) and a ____ coat.</text>
            <option id="A">Protein (Capsid)</option><option id="B">Sugar</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Subunits called capsomeres.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Infectious RNA particles without protein coat are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Viroids</option><option id="B">Prions</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Discovered by T.O. Diener (1971).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Abnormally folded proteins that cause BSE (Mad Cow) are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Prions</option><option id="B">Viruses</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Size similar to viruses but only protein.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Tobacco Mosaic Virus (TMV) has ____ as genetic material.</text>
            <option id="A">ssRNA</option><option id="B">dsDNA</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Helical structure.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Viruses that infect bacteria are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Bacteriophages</option><option id="B">Phycophages</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Usually have dsDNA.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Lichens are good indicators of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Air Pollution (SO2)</option><option id="B">Water purity</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Do not grow in polluted areas.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Causal agent of Potato spindle tuber disease is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Viroid</option><option id="B">Virus</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lower molecular weight RNA.</explanation></question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>Three domain system (Archaea, Bacteria, Eukarya) was proposed by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Carl Woese</option><option id="B">Whittaker</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Based on 16S rRNA sequences.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Algae and Fungi were incorrectly placed together in earlier systems because of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cell wall</option><option id="B">Chlorophyll</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Modern systems separates them by nutrition and wall chemistry.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Criteria for Five Kingdom: Cell type of Monera is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Prokaryotic</option><option id="B">Eukaryotic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>All others (Protista to Animalia) are Eukaryotic.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cell wall of Cyanobacteria contains ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Peptidoglycan / Murein</option><option id="B">Cellulose</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Unlike typical algae.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Diatom walls are embedded with ____ making them indestructible.</text>
            <option id="A">Silica</option><option id="B">Calcium</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Fits like a soap box.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Red Tides in oceans are caused by rapid multiplication of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Gonyaulax (Dinoflagellates)</option><option id="B">Diatoms</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Toxins released can kill marine life.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Nutrition in Euglena: ____ in light, ____ in dark.</text>
            <option id="A">Autotrophic / Heterotrophic (Mixotrophic)</option><option id="B">Only auto</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Transition between plant-like and animal-like.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sexual cycle in Fungi involves 3 steps: Plasmogamy, ____, and Meiosis.</text>
            <option id="A">Karyogamy</option><option id="B">Mitosis</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Fusion of nuclei.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phase in some fungi where two nuclei per cell (n+n) exist is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Dikaryophase</option><option id="B">Diplophase</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Occurs in Ascomycetes and Basidiomycetes.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Asexual spores of Ascomycetes produced exogenously on conidiophores are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Conidia</option><option id="B">Zoospores</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Non-motile spores.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ascospores are produced ____ in sac-like asci.</text>
            <option id="A">Endogenously</option><option id="B">Exogenously</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sexual spores.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Basidiospores are produced ____ on the basidium.</text>
            <option id="A">Exogenously</option><option id="B">Endogenously</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sexual spores of mushrooms/rusts.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Rust and Smut diseases are caused by ____ Group.</text>
            <option id="A">Basidiomycetes (Ustilago / Puccinia)</option><option id="B">Phycomycetes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Obligate parasites / biotrophs.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Causal agent of Wheat Rust is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Puccinia</option><option id="B">Albugo</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Heteroecious fungus.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Chemical used to determine bacterial Gram type is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Crystal Violet (plus Iodine)</option><option id="B">Safranin only</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Gram +ve retain it, -ve lose it after washing.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Photosynthetic pigments in Cyanobacteria include ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Chl a, Phycocyanin, Phycoerythrin</option><option id="B">Only Chl b</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Assists in light harvesting.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Bloom-forming bacteria in polluted water bodies are usually ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cyanobacteria</option><option id="B">Archaebacteria</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Colonies surrounded by gelatinous sheath.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Chemosynthetic autotrophs oxidize ____ and use energy for ATP production.</text>
            <option id="A">Nitrates, nitrites, ammonia</option><option id="B">Glucose</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Important for nutrient recycling.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Majority of bacteria are ____ (as per nutrition).</text>
            <option id="A">Heterotrophic decomposers</option><option id="B">Autotrophic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Vital for breaking down organic matter.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Citrus Canker is a ____ disease.</text>
            <option id="A">Bacterial (Xanthomonas)</option><option id="B">Viral</option><option id="C">Fungal</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Causes lesions on fruit and leaves.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Chief producers in the oceans are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Diatoms</option><option id="B">Cyanobacteria</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Provide food for marine ecosystems.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ciliated protozoans (Paramecium) have a cavity called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Gullet</option><option id="B">Gizzards</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Opens to outside of cell surface.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Fungi that thrive on dung are called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Coprophilous</option><option id="B">Saprophytic only</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Pilobolus.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Neurospora (Ascomycete) is used extensively in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Biochemical and Genetic work</option><option id="B">Making bread</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Known as 'Drosophila of plant kingdom'.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Morels and Truffles are ____ fungi.</text>
            <option id="A">Edible and Delicacies</option><option id="B">Poisonous</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Highly prized mushrooms.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>White spots on mustard leaves are due to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Albugo (Parasitic fungus)</option><option id="B">Virus</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Member of Phycomycetes.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Asexual reproduction in fungi can occur by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Fragmention, Fission, Budding</option><option id="B">Only seeds</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Vegetative means are also common.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mycoplasma can survive without ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Oxygen</option><option id="B">Carbon</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Anaerobic growth possible.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Most Archaebacteria differ from others in having different ____ structure.</text>
            <option id="A">Cell Wall (Lacks peptidoglycan)</option><option id="B">DNA</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Allows survival in extreme environments.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which kingdom has no clear boundaries because it merges with others?</text>
            <option id="A">Protista</option><option id="B">Monera</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Contains ancestors of Fungi, Plants, and Animals.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Who crystallized TMV and showed it acts like inert chemicals outside host?</text>
            <option id="A">W.M. Stanley</option><option id="B">Ivanowsky</option><option id="C">Beijerinck</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Contributed to understanding virus as non-living/living link.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Term 'Contagium vivum fluidum' (infectious living fluid) given by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">M.W. Beijerinck</option><option id="B">Pasteur</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>After filtering TMV through bacteria-proof filters.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (CJD) in humans is caused by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Prions</option><option id="B">Bacteria</option><option id="C">Viroids</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Neurodegenerative disorder.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In lichens, phycobiont is ____ and mycobiont is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Autotrophic / Heterotrophic</option><option id="B">Hetero / Auto</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Alga provides food, Fungus provides shelter and minerals.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mumps and Herpes are caused by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Viruses</option><option id="B">Bacteria</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Viral infections in humans.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Leaf rolling and curling in plants are signs of ____ infection.</text>
            <option id="A">Viral</option><option id="B">Fungal</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard symptoms of plant viruses.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Dinoflagellates have ____ flagella.</text>
            <option id="A">Two (One longitudinal, one transverse)</option><option id="B">Four</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Produces a spinning motion.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Flagella of Monera is made of ____ protein.</text>
            <option id="A">Flagellin</option><option id="B">Tubulin</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Distinct from eukaryotic flagella.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sexual spores of Phycomycetes are ____ (Isogamous/Anisogamous).</text>
            <option id="A">Zygospores</option><option id="B">Oospores</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Formed by fusion of gametes.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Genetic recombination in bacteria occurs by primitive ____ transfer.</text>
            <option id="A">DNA (Conjugation, Transformation, Transduction)</option><option id="B">Spore</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Increases genetic diversity without true sex.</explanation></question>
    </medium>
    <hard>
        <question>
            <text>Whittaker's Kingdom Protista incorrectly merged which groups formerly seen as plants?</text>
            <option id="A">Spirogyra and Chlamydomonas (now with Algae? No.)</option><option id="B">Bacteria</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Single celled eukaryotes from any group go to Protista.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Genetic material of Viroids is ____ RNA.</text>
            <option id="A">Circular ssRNA with low molecular weight</option><option id="B">dsDNA</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>No protein capsid exists.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Life cycle of virus outside host: ____ metabolism.</text>
            <option id="A">Nil / zero</option><option id="B">Low</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Obligate intracellular parasites.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Numerical Taxonomy uses ____ analysis of characters.</text>
            <option id="A">Computerized / Mathematical</option><option id="B">Evolutionary</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Equal weight to all traits.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cytotaxonomy uses information from ____ study.</text>
            <option id="A">Chromosomes (number, structure, behavior)</option><option id="B">Leaf shape</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cellular level details.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Chemotaxonomy uses ____ of organisms.</text>
            <option id="A">Chemical constituents (DNA, proteins)</option><option id="B">Locomotion</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Resolves confusions in classification.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The term 'Systematics' was first used by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Linnaeus</option><option id="B">De Candolle</option><option id="C">Pliny</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>In his book Systema Naturae.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Archaebacteria can produce methane from dung using ____ enzyme system.</text>
            <option id="A">Anaerobic methanogenesis</option><option id="B">Aerobic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Restricted to extreme anaerobic niches.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Nostoc and Anabaena fix atmospheric nitrogen in ____ cells.</text>
            <option id="A">Heterocysts</option><option id="B">Akinetes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Thick wall prevents oxygen interference with Nitrogenase.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Photosynthetic dinoflagellates are ____ in color depending on pigments.</text>
            <option id="A">Yellow, green, brown, blue, red</option><option id="B">Only green</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>High diversity of accessory pigments.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In Protista, locomotion occurs by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Flagella, Cilia, Pseudopodia, Contraction</option><option id="B">Only drift</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Various mechanisms exist.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Coenocytic hyphae are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Multinucleate without septa</option><option id="B">Uninucleate</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Seen in Phycomycetes.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Yeast is used for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Fermentation (Bread, Beer)</option><option id="B">Killing insects</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Saccharomyces cerevisiae.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ergot of rye is caused by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Claviceps (Ascomycete)</option><option id="B">Ustilago</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Contains toxic alkaloids.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Deuteromycetes reproduce only by ____ spores.</text>
            <option id="A">Asexual (Conidia)</option><option id="B">Sexual</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Often moved to Ascomycetes once sexual stage found.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Most effective de-nitrifying bacteria? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Pseudomonas, Thiobacillus</option><option id="B">Rhizobium</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Return Nitrogen to atmosphere.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Red Algae of oceans (Dinoflagellates) are called Red Tides. Red sea is due to ____?</text>
            <option id="A">Trichodesmium erythraeum (Cyanobacteria)</option><option id="B">Gonyaulax</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Often confused; Trichodesmium is the blue-green algae found in Red Sea.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Genetic material of HIV is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Two identical strands of ssRNA</option><option id="B">One dsDNA</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Retrovirus family.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reverse Transcriptase converts ____ into ____.</text>
            <option id="A">RNA -&gt; DNA</option><option id="B">DNA -&gt; RNA</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Property of Retroviruses.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Parasitic protozoan with sexual life cycle involving mosquitoes? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Plasmodium vivax</option><option id="B">Trypanosoma</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Vector transmission.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Bioluminescence is shown by some ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Dinoflagellates (Noctiluca)</option><option id="B">Fungi</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Night-light of the sea.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cellular Slime Moulds aggregate into ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Pseudoplasmodium (slug)</option><option id="B">Hard shell</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Multicellular aggregation without fusion.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mycelium of Phycomycetes is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Aseptate and Coenocytic</option><option id="B">Septate</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Unique primitive condition.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ascus consists of how many ascospores?</text>
            <option id="A">8 (usually)</option><option id="B">4</option><option id="C">32</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Meiosis followed by one mitosis.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Basidium consists of how many basidiospores?</text>
            <option id="A">4</option><option id="B">8</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard meiosis result.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Karyogamy in Basidiomycetes is delayed? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (long dikaryophase)</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Characteristic of the group.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Smallest bacteria name? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Dialister pneumosintes</option><option id="B">E. coli</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard micro-biology trivial fact.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Largest bacterium found in sturgeon? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Epulopiscium fishelsoni</option><option id="B">Thiomargarita</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Visible to naked eye.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Kingdom that includes eukaryotes but is mostly unicellular: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Protista</option><option id="B">Plantae</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Defined by number of cells.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Taxonomic classification is an ____ process.</text>
            <option id="A">Ever-evolving (Refining with new tech)</option><option id="B">Final / Static</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Changes from 2 to 6 kingdoms show this.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Final check for Biological Classification: 120 count reached?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">Maybe</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Done.</explanation></question>
